'''Livingston Ludlow Biddle Jr.''' (May 26, 1918 – May 3, 2002) was an [[United States|American]] author and promoter of funding of the arts, from a wealthy [[Pennsylvania]] family.
==Life== Livingston Ludlow Biddle was born in [[Bryn Mawr, Pennsylvania]], on May 26, 1918.<ref name="obit">{{cite news |author= David Stout |title=Livingston Biddle Jr., 83, Ex-Chairman of Arts Endowment | date= May 4, 2002 |url =https://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/04/us/livingston-biddle-jr-83-ex-chairman-of-arts-endowment.html | newspaper= The New York Times | pages =A11 |accessdate= March 16, 2011 }}</ref> His mother was Euginie Carter Law, and father was Livingston Ludlow Biddle (1877–1959) of the [[Biddle family]] of Philadelphia, who published poems such as "The Understanding Hills".<ref>{{cite book |title= The Understanding Hills, and other Poems |author= Livingston Ludlow Biddle |publisher= Dodd, Mead and Company |year= 1916 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=da8VAAAAYAAJ }}</ref> Ancestors included grandfather Edward Biddle (1851–1933) who married Emily Taylor Drexel (1851–1883), daughter of [[Anthony Joseph Drexel]], and great grandfather [[Nicholas Biddle (banker)|Nicholas Biddle]] (1786–1844), linking to two major banking families.<ref name="obit"/> He attended the Montgomery School in [[Chester Springs, Pennsylvania]] and [[St. George's School, Newport|St. George's School]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island]]. He graduated from [[Princeton University]] in 1940, majoring in English and French. He was also on the tennis team.<ref name="prince">{{cite news |title= Memorial: Livingston L. Biddle '40 |work= Princeton Alumni Weekly |date= October 9, 2002 |url= https://paw.princeton.edu/memorial/livingston-l-biddle-40 |accessdate= December 22, 2016 }}</ref>
He went to work as a reporter for the ''[[Philadelphia Bulletin]]'' newspaper until [[World War II]] broke out. Several of his cousins and uncles were military leaders, but his poor eyesight limited his service to driving ambulances in Africa. After the war he wrote short stories and four novels set in Philadelphia. From 1963 to 1965 he worked as staff assistant to Senator [[Claiborne Pell]], who was a classmate from both St. George's and Princeton. He helped draft the legislation creating the [[National Endowment for the Arts]] (NEA) and the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]]. He was appointed by President [[Jimmy Carter]] as the third chairman of the NEA in 1977 and served from 1981.<ref name="obit"/>
Biddle married Cordelia Fenton who died in 1972. In 1973 he married artist Catharina Baart (1912–2005), who had been born in the [[Netherlands]]. She taught art in the [[Washington, DC]] public schools from the 1950s to 1974.<ref>{{cite news |title= Catharina Baart Biddle: Artist, Teacher |newspaper= The Washington Post |date= February 26, 2005 |url= http://catharinabaartbiddle.com/index.htm |accessdate= March 16, 2011 |deadurl= yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110201052623/http://catharinabaartbiddle.com/index.htm |archivedate= February 1, 2011 |df= }}</ref>
He died May 3, 2002.<ref name="prince"/>
==Legacy== His daughter from his first marriage, Cordelia Frances Biddle (born 1947), also became an author. A series features the fictitious Philadelphia character Martha Beale.<ref>{{cite web |title= Historical Notes |author= Cordelia Frances Biddle |work= author web page |url= http://www.cordeliafrancesbiddle.com/docs/HistoricalNotes.html |accessdate= March 16, 2011 |deadurl= yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110518022431/http://cordeliafrancesbiddle.com/docs/HistoricalNotes.html |archivedate= May 18, 2011 |df= }}</ref>
